      devanagari: 'यतो यतो निश्चरति मनश्चञ्चलमस्थिरम् ।\nततस्ततो नियम्यैतदात्मन्येव वशं नयेत् ॥',
      transliteration: 'yato yato niścarati manaś cañcalam asthiram\ntatas tato niyamyaitad ātmany eva vaśaṁ nayet',
      translation: 'Wherever the restless and unsteady mind wanders, withdraw it from there and bring it back under the control of the self alone.',
      words: [
        { word: 'yataḥ yataḥ', meaning: 'wherever / from whichever place' },
        { word: 'niścarati manaḥ', meaning: 'the mind wanders / the mind moves away' },
        { word: 'cañcalam asthiram', meaning: 'restless and unsteady / moving and unstable' },
        { word: 'tatas tataḥ', meaning: 'from there / from each such place' },
        { word: 'niyamya etat', meaning: 'withdrawing this / restraining it' },
        { word: 'ātmani eva', meaning: 'back to the self alone / onto oneself' },
        { word: 'vaśam nayet', meaning: 'bring under control / lead to mastery' }
      ],
      commentary: `This verse contains the entire practice of meditation in two lines. The mind will wander. That is not a failure — it is what minds do. They are described here as cañcala (restless) and asthira (unsteady). These are not flaws to be condemned. They are simply the nature of the untrained mind, the way a young horse moves erratically before training.\n\nThe instruction is not to prevent the wandering — that is not possible, especially at the start. The instruction is to notice where the mind has gone, and bring it back. Again. And again. Yato yato — wherever. Tatas tataḥ — from there. Wherever it goes, from there, bring it back. The practice is the returning, not the staying.\n\nYour thoughts are lying to you — not maliciously, but because the mind has been trained by years of habit to run toward anxiety, comparison, regret, distraction. Every time you notice that it has run and you choose to return, you are retraining it. The practice is not dramatic. It is patient. It is repeated. And it is available in every moment.`,
