    27: {
      id: 27,
      name: 'Supreme Happiness Arrives',
      devanagari: 'प्रशान्तमनसं ह्येनं योगिनं सुखमुत्तमम् ।\nउपैति शान्तरजसं ब्रह्मभूतमकल्मषम् ॥',
      transliteration: 'praśānta-manasaṁ hy enaṁ yoginaṁ sukham uttamam\nupaiti śānta-rajasaṁ brahma-bhūtam akalmaṣam',
      translation: 'Supreme happiness comes to this yogi whose mind is completely at peace, whose rajas is stilled, who is free from sin, who has become Brahman.',
      words: [
        { word: 'praśānta-manasam hi enam yoginam', meaning: 'to this yogi whose mind is completely at peace' },
        { word: 'sukham uttamam upaiti', meaning: 'supreme happiness comes / approaches' },
        { word: 'śānta-rajasam', meaning: 'whose rajas is stilled / whose passionate quality is quieted' },
        { word: 'brahma-bhūtam', meaning: 'who has become Brahman / who has merged with the Absolute' },
        { word: 'akalmaṣam', meaning: 'free from sin / without impurity' }
      ],
      commentary: `The happiness described here — uttama sukha, supreme happiness — does not come to the yogi through effort. It comes to them: upaiti, it approaches. This is the nature of this particular joy. It cannot be seized or manufactured. It arrives when the conditions that have been blocking it are removed.\n\nThree conditions of the yogi who receives it: completely peaceful mind, stilled rajas (the quality of passion and agitation), and freedom from sin. Śānta-rajas is particularly significant. Rajas is not inherently bad — it is the energy of action and dynamism. But when it dominates, it produces the restlessness, the craving, the frantic doing that prevents the deeper stillness from manifesting. When rajas quiets, something else becomes audible.\n\nBrahma-bhūtam — having become Brahman. This is not a future destination. It is a description of the person's present reality. They have already made the recognition; the joy is a natural expression of that recognition. You do not work toward supreme happiness as a goal. You work to remove what obscures the happiness that is already the nature of what you are.`
    },

    28: {
      id: 28,
      name: 'Contact with Brahman',
      devanagari: 'युञ्जन्नेवं सदात्मानं योगी विगतकल्मषः ।\nसुखेन ब्रह्मसंस्पर्शमत्यन्तं सुखमश्नुते ॥',
      transliteration: 'yuñjann evaṁ sadātmānaṁ yogī vigata-kalmaṣaḥ\nsukhena brahma-saṁsparśam atyantaṁ sukham aśnute',
      translation: 'The yogi who is ever engaged in yoga in this way, freed from sin — easily experiences the infinite happiness of contact with Brahman.',
      words: [
        { word: 'yuñjan evam sadā ātmānam', meaning: 'ever engaging the self in yoga in this way' },
        { word: 'yogī vigata-kalmaṣaḥ', meaning: 'the yogi freed from sin / the practitioner whose impurities have gone' },
        { word: 'sukhena', meaning: 'easily / with ease' },
        { word: 'brahma-saṁsparśam', meaning: 'contact with Brahman / the touch of the Absolute' },
        { word: 'atyantam sukham aśnute', meaning: 'experiences infinite happiness / enjoys boundless joy' }
      ],
      commentary: `The word saṁsparśa — contact, touch — is intimate and direct. Not the indirect knowing-about of Brahman through philosophy or secondhand description. Actual contact. The touch of the Absolute on the prepared surface of a quieted mind.\n\nSukhena — easily. This is surprising and important. The practice may be long and sometimes difficult. But when it arrives, when the contact happens, it is experienced as easy — natural, effortless, as though it was always available and only the noise was in the way. The ease is the nature of the arrival, not of the journey.\n\nVigata-kalmaṣaḥ — freed from sin, with impurities removed. The freedom is again stated as a condition: the contact is not blocked by merit or demerit, by past action or future potential. It is blocked only by impurity — the accumulated obscurations of unexamined desire, habitual aversion, and mistaken identity. Remove these, through sustained practice, and the contact happens. Not as reward but as recognition.`
    },

