      commentary: `The fallen yogi does not fall into nothing. They first spend immeasurable time in the higher realms — the natural consequence of whatever genuine good was accumulated through the practice, however incomplete. This is the fruit of the good action itself, even unfinished.\n\nThen rebirth: in a pure and prosperous house — śucīnāṁ śrīmatāṁ gehe. Śuci means pure, clean, unsullied — the household is characterized by integrity and genuine spiritual aspiration. Śrīmat means prosperous, possessing śrī — the quality of auspicious abundance. The fallen yogi is given conditions for continuing: a family where the values of the path are alive, where the material conditions support the resumption of practice.\n\nThis is the Gita's understanding of karmic grace: the momentum of genuine practice does not dissipate between lives. It creates favorable conditions for the journey to continue. The next life is not a fresh start from zero. It is a continuation — with better conditions for going deeper.`
