      commentary: `The chapter closes with the highest designation: yuktatama — the most perfectly joined, the most completely united. Among all yogis — and yogis are already declared superior to ascetics, scholars, and ritual performers — this one is the best.\n\nThe quality is mad-gatena antar-ātmanā — inner self gone to me. Not outer behavior, not even intellectual orientation. The inner self itself has found its home in Krishna — in the reality that Krishna represents. This is not the beginning practitioner's effort. It is the arrival of someone whose inner being has genuinely relocated, whose center of gravity has fully shifted.\n\nŚraddhāvān — with faith. Even here, at the highest level, faith remains the defining quality. Not certainty as knowledge-from-outside, but śraddhā — the living orientation of the entire being toward truth, toward the highest, toward that which is real. The Gita began with this quality (in Chapter 4, verse 39) and returns to it here: faith is the beginning and the end of the path. The one who has faith in the deepest sense is already at the destination — they simply have not yet recognized it completely.`
